items.body:
@ErikRose suggested changing the way we do configuration overriding and do it instead as a context manager on the `ConfigManager`.

I like the fact it can be used as a context manager, class decorator and function decorator now. I think in order to keep the decorator functionality, we'd have to add the context manager, but otherwise keep things the way they are.

This definitely could use some more thought.

@pmac pointed out that `raise_error` is a mechanical name and not semantic, so it's not very descriptive and doesn't lend itself to obviousness in how/when you'd use it.

He suggested `required` or `missing_ok`.

I've seen `required` before. I think that'd be ok. The only thing that causes me pause is that I think changing it to `required` suggests a specific use case and I'm not sure offhand whether there are other use cases where the word "required" isn't clear.
